<definition><statement>
<p>
A <term>regular polygon</term> has all sides the same length and all angles the same measure.
</p>
 </statement>
</definition>
  
<p>
For example, squares are regular quadrilaterals &#8202;&#x2014;&#8202; all four sides are the same length, and all four angles measure <m>90^\circ</m>. But a non-square rectangle is <em>not regular</em>. Even though all of the angles are <m>90^\circ</m>, the sides are not all the same length. Similarly, a non-square rhombus is <em>not regular</em>. Even though the sides of a rhombus are all the same length, the angles can be different.
</p>
  <image source="images/" />  
<problem><statement>
<p>
Since a square is a regular quadrilateral, you know that every angle in a regular quadrilateral measure <m>90^\circ</m>. What about angles in other regular polygons?
</p>
